## Workflow Rules (anti-destructive)

### Planning
- Programs and session plans live under `.training.cto/`.
- Wait for approval before large custom programs when the user asked for analysis only (unless `-y`).
- Confirm before editing when scope is unclear.

### Deletion
- **NEVER delete files** without explicit user permission in the same message.
- Never `rm -rf` project trees, wipe `.training.cto/`, or truncate learner history "to clean up."
- Temp cleanup is limited to files **this session created** under `tmp/` / `.tmp/` — still prefer asking if unsure.

### Overwrite & merge
- Prefer **no-overwrite** / append / merge. Never wholesale-replace `.cursorrules`, active programs, or HANDOFF without explicit request.
- Deploy `update` lists merge candidates; agent merges rules-aware — does not blind-replace.

### Git
- NEVER `git commit` or `git push` unless the user explicitly requests it in the same message.
- Never modify history (**rebase, amend of others' commits, force-push**) without explicit request.
- Never update git config.
- When the user requests commit: stage safe paths, commit, show `git log -1 --oneline` + `git status -sb`; no "committed" claim without a SHA.
- Provide commit commands for the user when they will commit themselves.

### No attribution / no signatures
- Never add "Generated by", "Created by", dates-as-signatures, or agent signatures to files.
- **No `Co-authored-by:` trailers (mandatory)** — never add co-author trailers (Cursor/Copilot/any agent) or `--trailer`.

### Target-repo coexistence
- When scaffolding into a repo that already has Agent OS / app code: do not rewrite app source, dependencies, or CI unless asked.
- Route engineering/UI/biz work to the matching director / `@x-director` — do not invent parallel destructive "fixes" in the target codebase from CTO training sessions.

